<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the `sys_script` (Business Rule)
    row that auto-populates the `closed_date` field on every `x_casemgmt_case`
    record whose `status` transitions from "Resolved" to "Closed", inside the
    scoped application `x_casemgmt`.

    PURPOSE (AAP Section 0.5.5 verbatim):
        From       To       Required condition                                   Behavior
        Resolved   Closed   Caller has x_casemgmt_case_manager role; auto-set    surface form-level error
                            closed_date                                          on failure

    PURPOSE (AAP Section 0.5.7 verbatim):
        Field         Type        Constraints
        closed_date   DateTime    Auto-set on Close transition

    This Business Rule is the ServiceNow-native equivalent of ArkCase's
    server-side close-timestamp population in
    acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/java/com/
    armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/service/ChangeCaseFileStateService.java
    line 79-114 - specifically line 99:
            if ("CLOSED".equals(newState))
            {
                retval.setClosed(now);
            }
    The ArkCase implementation read the new state, compared against the
    string literal "CLOSED" (uppercase), and called retval.setClosed(now)
    to stamp the JPA-mapped `cm_case_closed` column (declared on
    acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/java/com/
    armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/model/CaseFile.java line 171-173 as
    @Column(name = "cm_case_closed") @Temporal(TemporalType.TIMESTAMP)
    private Date closed). The ServiceNow target preserves the same
    semantic - "stamp the close timestamp at the moment a case enters
    the Closed terminal state" - but adapts it to the platform's
    declarative Business Rule mechanism with three intentional
    differences:

      1) Title Case status comparison ('Resolved'/'Closed') instead of
         the ArkCase UPPERCASE comparison ('CLOSED'). The Title Case
         labels are the verbatim choice values defined in
         ../choices/sys_choice_case_status.xml per AAP Section 0.5.7,
         and they are stored on the row as-is - ServiceNow Choice
         fields persist the LABEL string by default, not an integer ID
         or an UPPERCASE-normalized form.

      2) Transition-detection (Resolved -> Closed) instead of
         single-state-detection (-> CLOSED). The ArkCase service was
         only invoked from the explicit ChangeCaseStatus pipeline, so
         it could safely set closed_date on any incoming "CLOSED"
         transition without checking the prior state. The ServiceNow
         Business Rule fires on EVERY before-update of x_casemgmt_case,
         regardless of caller (form, Table API, scripted REST,
         GlideRecord script, bulk import). To avoid stamping closed_date
         on (for example) a re-save of an already-Closed case from an
         administrative correction, the rule explicitly compares
         previous.status === 'Resolved' AND current.status === 'Closed',
         which uniquely identifies the lifecycle transition rather
         than the steady state. Note that direct insertion of a Closed
         case (status = Closed at insert time, with no prior Resolved
         step) is a separate code path and is NOT covered by this
         before-UPDATE rule - that path is exercised only by the seed
         data XML files (../seed-data/cases/x_casemgmt_case_demo_06.xml
         and ../seed-data/cases/x_casemgmt_case_demo_10.xml), which
         carry an explicit closed_date column value and intentionally
         bypass this Business Rule via the .nil() check.

      3) Defensive .nil() guard against double-write. The ArkCase
         service set the column unconditionally because it ran inside
         the same transaction as the state change and there was no
         risk of a parallel writer. The ServiceNow target has a
         second writer for the same column - the Flow Designer
         subflow ../flows/sub_flows/validate_closed_transition.xml -
         and the seed data carries explicit synthetic close
         timestamps. The .nil() guard prevents this rule from
         overwriting any of those authoritative values.

    BEHAVIOR:
        - Trigger          : BEFORE UPDATE only on the `x_casemgmt_case` table
        - Condition        : previous.status == 'Resolved' AND
                             current.status == 'Closed' AND
                             current.closed_date is nil/empty
        - Action           : sets current.closed_date = gs.nowDateTime()
        - Other timing     : does NOT fire on insert, delete, or query

    DEFENSIVE FIELD-SET (.nil() GUARD):
        The script uses current.closed_date.nil() to check whether the field
        is already populated. If the caller (seed data, Flow Designer
        subflow validate_closed_transition, manual administrative update)
        has already provided an explicit closed_date value, the script
        does NOT overwrite. This intentionally allows:

            (a) Seed data demos in
                ../seed-data/cases/x_casemgmt_case_demo_06.xml (General
                Inquiry, Closed) and
                ../seed-data/cases/x_casemgmt_case_demo_10.xml (Complaint,
                Closed) to specify synthetic closed_date timestamps that
                pair with the synthetic opened_date timestamps to give the
                "Average Time to Close" single-score widget on the Manager
                View dashboard (../reports/x_casemgmt_avg_time_to_close.xml)
                a non-zero, deterministic, demo-friendly value on a
                freshly-imported PDI. Note: the demo cases are inserted
                with status=Closed, so the BEFORE-UPDATE trigger of THIS
                rule does not even fire for them; the .nil() guard is
                relevant primarily to (b) below, plus any future
                re-update of an already-Closed case that somehow re-enters
                the Resolved -> Closed transition (which itself would be
                blocked by ../business_rules/x_casemgmt_block_terminal_closed.xml,
                but defense in depth).

            (b) The Flow Designer subflow
                ../flows/sub_flows/validate_closed_transition.xml, which
                fires on the same Resolved -> Closed transition through
                the user-facing flow path, also writes
                current.closed_date = gs.nowDateTime() inside a Set
                Field Value action. Both writers landing on the same
                row in the same transaction is harmless because:
                  * The .nil() guard means whichever writer fires FIRST
                    populates the value, and the SECOND writer sees a
                    non-nil column and exits without re-stamping;
                  * Even if both writers fired and both wrote, both
                    would write the same gs.nowDateTime() value (within
                    millisecond precision in the same transaction), so
                    the net effect is identical to a single write.
                The redundancy is INTENTIONAL: the flow catches
                interactive transitions through the form/UI; this BR
                catches direct DB modifications (Table API, scripted
                REST endpoints, server scripts, bulk imports) that
                bypass the Flow Designer entry point.

        For organic Resolved -> Closed transitions that flow through any
        other path (direct Table API PATCH, GlideRecord.update() in an
        ad-hoc admin script, a future scripted REST endpoint that
        bypasses the flow), the script populates closed_date with the
        current platform time so downstream reports and the Manager
        View dashboard never see a null closed_date for a Closed case.

    DICTIONARY READ-ONLY OVERRIDE:
        The closed_date field is declared read_only=true at the dictionary
        level in ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_closed_date.xml. ServiceNow
        intentionally exempts server-side Business Rule scripts from
        dictionary read_only enforcement so this rule can write the field
        even though end-users cannot edit it on the form. This pattern is
        the canonical way to populate auto-set audit-style domain fields
        whose value is system-managed but whose presence on the row is
        critical for downstream reporting (the avg-time-to-close widget
        is the primary consumer per AAP Section 0.4.1 Manager View
        Dashboard widget inventory).

    PORTAL UPDATE COMPATIBILITY:
        The unauthenticated submission endpoint at
        ../portal/rest/sys_ws_definition_x_casemgmt_case_submit.xml
        creates new cases in Draft (not Closed), so this BEFORE-UPDATE
        rule does NOT fire on portal submission. The lookup endpoint at
        ../portal/rest/sys_ws_definition_x_casemgmt_case_status_lookup.xml
        is read-only and never updates the row. Therefore neither portal
        endpoint interacts with this rule. The portal lookup explicitly
        EXCLUDES closed_date from its whitelisted output fields per AAP
        Section 0.7.4 ("the lookup page returns ONLY status, subject,
        opened_date") - so even though this rule populates closed_date
        on internal transitions, that timestamp is never exposed to
        anonymous external requesters.

    ORDERING WITHIN BEFORE-UPDATE PHASE:
        order=500 is intentionally HIGH so this rule runs LAST among the
        before-update rules in this scoped application. The full
        before-update execution order in this folder is:

            1) x_casemgmt_block_terminal_closed.xml          (order=100, FIRST)
            2) x_casemgmt_block_draft_backtransition.xml     (order=200)
            3) x_casemgmt_validate_assigned_agent_membership (order=300)
            4) x_casemgmt_clear_pending_reason_on_inprogress (order=400)
            5) x_casemgmt_set_closed_date.xml                (order=500, LAST)

        Running LAST is critical because:
          * If x_casemgmt_block_terminal_closed (order=100) aborts the
            update because the previous.status was already Closed, this
            rule MUST be skipped - we never want to stamp closed_date on
            a transition that the platform is about to reject. ServiceNow
            short-circuits the BR pipeline on abort, so a higher order
            ensures we run only after all guards have passed.
          * If x_casemgmt_block_draft_backtransition (order=200) aborts
            the update because current.status == 'Draft', this rule MUST
            be skipped (the transition won't happen, so no close
            timestamp should be stamped).
          * Symmetric reasoning applies to orders 300 and 400.
          * After all guards pass and the platform is committed to the
            transition, this rule fires last and stamps the close
            timestamp as the final step of the before-update phase,
            immediately before the platform writes the row. The
            platform's database write therefore sees a fully-populated
            row including a freshly-stamped closed_date.

        There is no other before-update rule in this scoped application
        that reads closed_date, so the high order does not currently
        conflict with anything; 500 leaves room above (lower numbers
        run earlier) and below for future expansion.

    EMAIL-DISABLED CONSTRAINT (AAP Section 0.7.2):
        The script body MUST NOT call gs.eventQueue('...') for any email
        notification event since email is disabled on the PDI. This rule
        contains zero gs.eventQueue() calls, zero gs.email() calls, and
        zero gs.notificationEngine() calls. It performs only the field-set
        operation. This intentionally diverges from ArkCase, where
        ChangeCaseFileStateService line 106 raised an event via
        getCaseFileEventUtility().raiseEvent(...) which would have
        triggered downstream notification listeners; the ServiceNow POC
        omits the equivalent gs.eventQueue('case.closed', ...) call
        per the AAP minimal-change clause.

    SCOPED-NAMESPACE CONSTRAINT (AAP Section 0.7.2):
        - <collection>x_casemgmt_case</collection>     scoped table
        - <sys_scope>x_casemgmt</sys_scope>            scoped namespace
        - <sys_package>x_casemgmt</sys_package>        scoped application
        - script body references current.closed_date  scoped field
        - script body references previous.status      scoped field
        - script body references current.status       scoped field
        Zero global-scope writes. Zero modifications to OOB tables.

    NO-HARDCODED-SYS_ID CONSTRAINT (AAP Section 0.7.2):
        - <collection> resolves the case table BY NAME (x_casemgmt_case)
        - <sys_scope> resolves the scope record BY NAME (x_casemgmt)
        - <sys_package> resolves the application record BY NAME (x_casemgmt)
        - The script body performs ZERO GlideRecord lookups by sys_id
          literal; it operates only on the platform-injected `current`
          and `previous` GlideRecord pair (the row being updated and
          its prior state).
        - The script body uses NO gs.getReference() calls and NO
          GlideRecord.get(sys_id) calls.
        - The <sys_id> element below is THIS record's own deterministic
          primary key (MD5 of "x_casemgmt_set_closed_date"), which is
          permitted because the AAP "no hardcoded sys_id" rule applies
          to REFERENCE FIELDS pointing at OTHER records, not to a
          record's own primary key.

    UPDATE-SET LOAD ORDER (AAP Section 0.5.2):
        This sys_script record MUST be loaded AFTER:
            - ../tables/x_casemgmt_case.xml             (table this rule attaches to)
            - ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_status.xml  (field this rule reads via previous/current)
            - ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_closed_date.xml (field this rule writes)
            - ../app/sys_app/x_casemgmt_case_management.xml (scoped application)
            - ../app/sys_scope/x_casemgmt.xml           (scope record)
            - ../choices/sys_choice_case_status.xml     (the Resolved/Closed
                                                         choice values that
                                                         this rule's script
                                                         compares against)
        And BEFORE:
            - ../seed-data/cases/x_casemgmt_case_demo_06.xml,
              ../seed-data/cases/x_casemgmt_case_demo_10.xml
              (the two Closed demo cases insert into x_casemgmt_case at
               status=Closed; the BEFORE-UPDATE trigger of this rule does
               NOT fire on those inserts, but the rule must be present
               in the schema before any subsequent update of those rows
               could plausibly trigger it)
            - ../flows/sub_flows/validate_closed_transition.xml
              (the Flow Designer subflow that ALSO sets closed_date
               on the Resolved -> Closed transition - defense in depth)

    DETERMINISTIC SYS_ID:
        sys_id = MD5("x_casemgmt_set_closed_date")
               = f6d63b3856121cac9b69215b2c46f64c
        32-character lowercase hex. The PDI accepts any valid 32-char hex
        sys_id; deriving from the record name guarantees idempotent re-import
        on a fresh PDI: re-importing the same Update Set produces the same
        sys_id, which collides on the existing record and updates it in place
        rather than creating a duplicate. This is the same convention used
        by the sibling Business Rule
        ../business_rules/x_casemgmt_set_opened_date.xml whose sys_id is
        MD5("x_casemgmt_set_opened_date") = c56aeecd4086f111be2867faae9e55ad.

    VALIDATION GATE MAPPING (AAP Section 0.7.3):
        - Gate 2 (Workflow): "All state transitions enforced for both case
          types - Invalid transitions return blocking error; task-closure
          check blocks Resolved transition". This rule completes the
          Resolved -> Closed transition by populating closed_date so the
          terminal state is fully recorded. Without this, the transition
          would technically succeed (status would change to Closed) but
          the close timestamp would be null, breaking the
          time-to-close downstream report.
        - Gate 6 (Dashboards): "Both dashboards render with synthetic
          data - All widgets display data; no broken report references".
          The Manager View dashboard's "Average Time to Close"
          single-score widget at ../reports/x_casemgmt_avg_time_to_close.xml
          computes AVG(closed_date - opened_date) over Closed cases.
          This rule guarantees closed_date is populated for every Closed
          case reached via the standard transition path, so the average
          is computed over a complete population (the seed-data Closed
          cases provide the synthetic baseline; this rule ensures any
          ad-hoc Closed transition during demo/validation also feeds
          the average correctly).
        - Gate 7 (Update Set): "Scoped app exported - Update Set loads
          without errors on a fresh PDI instance". The deterministic
          sys_id and reference-by-name pattern ensure this rule re-imports
          cleanly with zero preview errors.

    NO PII (AAP Section 0.7.2):
        The script body, code comments, and description text contain
        zero real names, real email addresses, real phone numbers, real
        organizational identifiers, or any other personally identifiable
        information. The rule operates exclusively on the synthetic
        case-status enumeration and a UTC timestamp.
-->
<record_update table="sys_script">
    <sys_script action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        <abort_action>false</abort_action>
        <access>package_private</access>
        <action_delete>false</action_delete>
        <action_insert>false</action_insert>
        <action_query>false</action_query>
        <action_update>true</action_update>
        <active>true</active>
        <add_message>false</add_message>
        <advanced>true</advanced>
        <change_fields>false</change_fields>
        <client_callable>false</client_callable>
        <collection>x_casemgmt_case</collection>
        <condition/>
        <description>Before-update on x_casemgmt_case: when previous.status == 'Resolved' AND current.status == 'Closed', sets current.closed_date = gs.nowDateTime() if not already populated. Replaces ArkCase ChangeCaseFileStateService.changeCaseState() retval.setClosed(now) (line 99 in acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/java/com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/service/ChangeCaseFileStateService.java). Per AAP Section 0.5.5 (Resolved-&gt;Closed auto-sets closed_date) and AAP Section 0.5.7 (closed_date DateTime, Auto-set on Close transition). Order=500 ensures this rule runs LAST among before-update rules so it only fires after all transition guards (block_terminal_closed, block_draft_backtransition, validate_assigned_agent_membership, clear_pending_reason_on_inprogress) have passed. Defensive .nil() guard preserves authoritative pre-set values from seed data and the validate_closed_transition Flow Designer subflow. Defense in depth with the subflow is intentional - this BR catches direct DB updates (Table API, scripted REST, GlideRecord scripts), the subflow catches interactive transitions through the form/UI. Contains zero gs.eventQueue() calls per the email-disabled constraint.</description>
        <execute_function>false</execute_function>
        <filter_condition/>
        <is_rest>false</is_rest>
        <message/>
        <name>x_casemgmt_set_closed_date</name>
        <order>500</order>
        <priority>100</priority>
        <rest_method/>
        <rest_method_text/>
        <rest_service/>
        <rest_service_text/>
        <rest_variables/>
        <role_conditions/>
        <script><![CDATA[(function executeRule(current, previous /*null when async*/) {
    // ServiceNow-native equivalent of ArkCase
    // ChangeCaseFileStateService.changeCaseState() line 99:
    //     if ("CLOSED".equals(newState)) { retval.setClosed(now); }
    // (acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/java/com/
    //  armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/service/ChangeCaseFileStateService.java)
    //
    // Per AAP Section 0.5.5: Resolved -> Closed transition auto-sets closed_date.
    // Per AAP Section 0.5.7: closed_date is "DateTime, Auto-set on Close transition".
    //
    // This BR runs alongside the Flow Designer subflow
    // ../flows/sub_flows/validate_closed_transition.xml; the redundancy is
    // intentional - this BR catches direct DB modifications (Table API,
    // scripted REST, GlideRecord scripts, bulk imports), the flow catches
    // interactive transitions through the form/UI.
    //
    // Order=500 ensures this rule runs LAST among before-update rules; if
    // any earlier guard aborted the action (block_terminal_closed at
    // order=100, block_draft_backtransition at order=200,
    // validate_assigned_agent_membership at order=300,
    // clear_pending_reason_on_inprogress at order=400), this BR is skipped.
    // We never stamp closed_date on a transition that's about to be
    // rejected.
    //
    // Defensive previous-null guard: the `previous` GlideRecord is null in
    // certain async/system contexts. If there is no previous state, no
    // transition can be detected, and the rule does nothing. The String()
    // cast normalizes the GlideElement to a primitive string for safe
    // === comparison; without the cast, GlideElement-vs-string equality
    // can behave inconsistently across releases.
    var prevStatus = previous ? String(previous.status) : '';
    var newStatus = String(current.status);

    // Verbatim Title Case status values per AAP Section 0.5.7 and the
    // sibling choice list ../choices/sys_choice_case_status.xml. The
    // labels ARE the stored values - ServiceNow Choice fields persist
    // the LABEL string by default, not an integer ID.
    if (prevStatus === 'Resolved' && newStatus === 'Closed') {
        // Defensive .nil() guard: respect pre-set values from the
        // Flow Designer subflow (which fires in the same transaction
        // for interactive transitions and may have already stamped
        // the column) and from any future seed-data path that updates
        // an already-loaded case from Resolved to Closed. Without this
        // guard, a value already written by the subflow would be
        // overwritten by gs.nowDateTime() at this rule's execution
        // point - harmless in practice (both writers produce the same
        // millisecond-precision timestamp within a single transaction)
        // but unnecessary and slightly less clear in audit logs.
        if (current.closed_date.nil()) {
            current.closed_date = gs.nowDateTime();
        }
    }
})(current, previous);
]]></script>
        <sys_class_name>sys_script</sys_class_name>
        <sys_created_by>admin</sys_created_by>
        <sys_created_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_created_on>
        <sys_domain>global</sys_domain>
        <sys_domain_path>/</sys_domain_path>
        <sys_id>f6d63b3856121cac9b69215b2c46f64c</sys_id>
        <sys_mod_count>0</sys_mod_count>
        <sys_name>x_casemgmt_set_closed_date</sys_name>
        <sys_overrides/>
        <sys_package display_value="Case Management" source="x_casemgmt">x_casemgmt</sys_package>
        <sys_policy/>
        <sys_scope display_value="Case Management">x_casemgmt</sys_scope>
        <sys_update_name>sys_script_x_casemgmt_set_closed_date</sys_update_name>
        <sys_updated_by>admin</sys_updated_by>
        <sys_updated_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_updated_on>
        <template/>
        <when>before</when>
    </sys_script>
</record_update>
